    question: 'How long does the Impatriati tax benefit last?',
    answer: 'Under the new regime (applicable to transfers from 2024 onward), the benefit lasts exactly <strong>5 tax years</strong> starting from the year you establish Italian tax residency. Unlike the old regime, there are no extensions or renewals. For example, if you move to Italy in 2026, you benefit for 2026 through 2030, and from 2031 your income is taxed at the standard rates.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do I apply for the Impatriati regime as an employee?',
    answer: 'No prior approval from the Agenzia delle Entrate (Italian Revenue Agency) is required. As an employee, you submit a written self-certification to your employer declaring that you meet all eligibility requirements. Your employer then applies the 50% exemption directly in your payslip (busta paga). You must also report the subsidised income correctly in your annual tax return (Modello 730 or Modello Redditi PF). Keep documentation proving your foreign residence during the preceding years (foreign employment contracts, utility bills, rental agreements).',
  },
